NAME
       man - an interface to the system reference manuals

SYNOPSIS
       man [OPTION...] [SECTION] PAGE...

DESCRIPTION
       man is the system's manual pager.  Each  page  argument  given  to
       man is normally the name of a program, utility or function.  The
       manual page associated with each of these arguments is then found
       and displayed.  A section, if provided, will restrict the search
       to that section only.

OPTIONS
       -f, --whatis
              equivalent to whatis; display a brief description of each
              page argument from the manual page NAME section

       -k, --apropos
              equivalent to apropos; search all man page NAME sections
              for keywords

       -w, --where, --path, --location
              print the location of the manual page file(s) that would
              be displayed

       -a, --all
              display all matching manual pages (not just the first)

       -s, --sections=LIST
              restrict search to colon-separated LIST of sections

       --help display this help and exit

       --version
              output version information and exit

INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
       The manual page is displayed in an interactive pager with the
       following commands:

       SPACE, PgDn, f
              scroll forward one page

       b, PgUp
              scroll backward one page

       Down, j, RETURN
              scroll forward one line

       Up, k  scroll backward one line

       Home, g
              go to beginning

       End, G go to end

       /pattern
              search forward for pattern

       n      next search match

       N      previous search match

       q      quit

SEARCH PATH
       man searches for pages in /usr/share/man/man<section>/, defaulting
       to section 1.  Page files are named <name>.<section> (e.g.,
       ls.1).

EXIT STATUS
       0      if OK

       1      no manual entry found

       2      if errors occurred

